Let $x=3 x_{1}$ and $y=3 y_{1}$, then $3 x_{1}^{2}+3 y_{1}^{2}=z^{2}, z$ is divisible by 3; assuming $z=3 z_{1}$, we get $x_{1}^{2}+y_{1}^{2}=3 z_{1}^{2}$, where $x_{1}<x, y_{1}<y, z_{1}<z$. Continuing this process further, we will arrive at an equation where:

1) either all three numbers $x, y, z$ are equal to one, which is impossible since $1^{2}+1^{2} \neq 3 \cdot 1^{2}$;
2) or one of the numbers $x$ and $y$ is equal to one, which is impossible since $1^{2}+(3 k)^{2} \neq 3(3 m)^{2}$;
3) or $z=1$, which is impossible since $(3 k)^{2}+$ $+(3 m)^{2} \neq 3$

From this, we conclude that the equation $x^{2}+y^{2}=3 z^{2}$ has no solutions in integers.

